<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-907-824  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 907 824.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Nov 21 1989 v3 n42 p27(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Utility puts art in PostScript font. (The Art Importer) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Altsys Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   PostScript (Printer software) (computer programs)The Art Importer (Computer graphics software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionGraphics SoftwareUtility ProgramsFonts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Carolyn SaidandM;Plano, Texas -- Altsys Corp. this month shipped The Art Importer, a $179utility that lets users turn artwork into PostScript fonts.andM;An upgrade to the company's earlier $99 KeyMaster program, the new versionadds:andM;andgt;The capability to create fonts with up to 256 characters (memorypermitting), eliminating KeyMaster's 16-character limit.andM;andgt;Support for images imported from TypeStyler, a type-manipulation programfrom Broderbund Software of San Rafael, Calif., and Streamline, an auto-traceprogram from Adobe Systems Inc. of Mountain View, Calif.andM;andgt;Limited support for color.andP;  Art Importer fonts appear on screen in black andwhite but can be output in color if they were based originally on colorartwork.andM;Like KeyMaster, The Art Importer lets users create PostScript fonts fromEncapsulated PostScript images generated in Aldus FreeHand or AdobeIllustrator as well as from PICT or PICT2 graphics generated inobject-oriented drawing programs such as MacDraw II or SuperPaint.andP;  Theimages can then be entered with a keystroke in virtually any Mac program.andM;&quot;It's a unique way of getting custom designs into a font format,&quot; said DougEvans, vice president of New York-based PDR Impressions, a design, typographyand pre-press company.andM;Smaller file sizes are another advantage, he said.andP;  &quot;You can use a piece ofart-work thousands of times without increasing the file size.andP;  An image withrepeating elements that would consume 5 or 6 Mbytes in Illustrator might takeonly 25 or 30 Kbytes when the graphics are transformed into a font with TheArt Importer.&quot;andM;KeyMaster users can buy The Art Importer for $20.andM;Altsys Corp. is at 720 Avenue F, Suite 109, Plano, Texas 75074; (214)424-4888.andO;</TEXT></DOC>